              <tr> 
                <td height="622" valign="top" colspan="2" bgcolor="#004142">&nbsp;<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">Increasing turnout at your Tournament</font></td></tr></table><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Rating</Font></TD><TD><IMG SRC="images/a4.gif" BORDER=0><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=862"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=862"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=2464">Scott "DieLukeDie" Gaeta</A></FONT></TD></TR><!-- 2464 --><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Description</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">How I have grown our local tournament over the last two years from 8 players to 30.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Article</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">	   Increasing turnout at your Tournaments<br>
<br>
<br>
     First of all, let me tell you a little bit about me.  My name is Scott Gaeta and I run about forty tournaments a year.  The average turnout for my tournaments are from 20-30 players.  I didn't always get  this large of a turn out, but by doing the things  I will discuss in this article, it has grown to become a tournament where players of all skill levels can come to play and be challenged by a wide variety of players.  So lets get to it.<br>
<br>
     Consistancy is the first key to building a successful tournament.	It is hard to get any momentum going if you don't have a set schedule of when your tournaments will be.  I am a firm believer that the more frequent your tournaments are, the more the player base will grow.  We as players spend a lot of time, money, and effort on this game, and if we don't have a chance to play, we loose interest.	In my case, tournaments are held weekly and this gives the player more incentive to build new decks, playtest, etc.  You will have to base your frequency on your area. Bi-weekly or monthly may be good for your area.  Whichever it is make it consistant.	I have talked to some people who believe that a weekly tournament just burns people out.  I could not disagree more.  Players want to play.  Now that's not to say every person will play every week.	We all have lives outside of card games. (Right?)  The other thing you will notice is the level of play will increase.	After all, as they say, practice makes perfect.  (I have recently seen players in my area go from placing in the bottom five to the top ten.  This in a tournament in which there are always ten or so players with a 1700+ rating).<br>
<br>
     Location is also important.  If your players know that every Saturday at noon there is a tournament at 'Bob's Game Shop' it becomes a regular happening.  Your players can look forward to and plan for it.  Find a store that has ample seating and room to grow.  If you can help it, don't restrict yourself  to a location with very limited seating.  There is nothing worse than turning players away.  If you do turn players away they we probably think twice about coming back.<br>
<br>
<br>
     Entry Fee's. Definetly charge one.  At my tournaments it's $3.00 and I turn 100% of it into prizes.  Because you know there's only so much white border premiere one can take. (Reflections is a huge hit).<br>
<br>
<br>
     Prizes are definitely an important part of a tournament.  After all, who doesn't like opening packs of cards or getting a cool Star Wars t-shirt?  Spread out the prizes.  Make sure everyone who plays gets at least one pack of cards. (I do 2 per minimum)  They did pay $3.00,  after all.  Also, don't heap all the prizes on first place.	(A tournament in this state used to give the winner the whole box of Premiere - and that was it.  That tournament no longer exists today.)  Once again, location comes into play here.	Try to find a shop that will turn 100% of the entry fee into packs of cards, Enhanced packs, T-shirts whatever.   Some shops may be short sighted and want, say, $1.00 a head or some such nonsense.  This is where you need to explain to them  that you're trying to grow a player base and $1.00 a head is nothing compared to 10, 20, or 30+ serious gamers coming into their shop on a regular basis.  If you have a really good relationship with the shop, they may even sell you these prizes at a discount. This way, you can stretch the prize dollar even more.  Another thing you can try is see if the shop will trade the box of white border premiere you have for a box of other cards on occasion.  Just something to mix things up.<br>
<br>
<br>
     E-Mails.  Don't just rely on the Decipher Web site to keep your players informed.  Send out an e-mail from time to time with a tournament schedule, directions, a prize list, etc.  Also listing the standings from the last tournament is nice.	Everyone like to see theire name in print.<br>
<br>
<br>
     Be Professional.  You set the tone.  Keep things moving and be consistant.  Have a glossary handy.  Always remember it's only a game, and remind those who get a little to worked up the same thing.<br>
<br>
<br>
     Teaching Decks.  Have two balanced teaching decks on hand.  You will always have that person who stumbles upon the tournament and would like to learn how to play.  There is no better way to increase your turnout than by creating new players.<br>
<br>
<br>
     Have fun with your tournament.  Some of the  things I have done are:<br>
1. Give a pack to the first player to turn Luke to the dark side or the first player to complete an attack run, etc.<br>
2. Have a house rule when anybody uses Chewbacca of Kashyyyk's defensive roar they have to roar.<br>
3. Give a pack to the player who gets stuck with the bye.<br>
4. Do a random drawing for something cool. (I'm planning a Bounty Tournament in the near future where any player who beats a Squadron member will either win a pack, or be entered in a drawing for something cool like a EJP pack.)<br>
<br>
Remember, if you are having fun, so will your players.	 A few months back, a player who really doesn't have a good chance to win a tournament came with an Attack Run deck.  Every time he blew up the Death Star, (which he did twice) he stood on his chair and yelled 'I blew up the Death Star baby!'	 Now this was a guy having fun!<br>
<br>
<br>
     Well, I hope I have given you some good ideas.  If you have any to share feel free to e-mail me or write your own article.  Remember it takes time and effort to build your player base.  Though I think it's definetly worth it.  Running tournament with 20+ players is so much more interesting than just the 8 player minimum.<br>
<br>
Best,<br>
Scott<br>
